41
00:02:48,320 --> 00:02:53,280
But the thesis was that if you started fooling around with AI

42
00:02:53,280 --> 00:02:57,120
and you got really fast supercomputers,

43
00:02:57,120 --> 00:03:02,320
then maybe the thing would start evolving.

44
00:03:02,320 --> 00:03:05,640
Because if you can't solve a problem, what do you do?

45
00:03:05,640 --> 00:03:08,520
You try a lot of things, and then you

46
00:03:08,520 --> 00:03:13,720
see which of them seem to be leading to some improvement.

47
00:03:13,720 --> 00:03:16,160
And then you collect the programs

48
00:03:16,160 --> 00:03:18,720
that seem to make a little progress

49
00:03:18,720 --> 00:03:22,560
and mix their parts and recombine them.

50
00:03:22,560 --> 00:03:29,080
And in fact, maybe half a dozen projects in the last 50 years

51
00:03:29,080 --> 00:03:31,820
have been people who said, oh, instead

52
00:03:31,820 --> 00:03:34,600
of trying to program an intelligent machine,

53
00:03:34,600 --> 00:03:37,960
why don't we just evolve one by generating

54
00:03:37,960 --> 00:03:40,840
lots of random code and giving it problems

55
00:03:40,840 --> 00:03:45,480
and selecting the ones that work and taking pieces of their DNA

56
00:03:45,480 --> 00:03:47,880
and recombining them?

57
00:03:47,880 --> 00:03:51,160
And there's about a dozen such programs,

58
00:03:51,160 --> 00:03:54,200
