01:42:31,540 --> 01:42:35,980
hard, try to achieve, like you said,

1578
01:42:35,980 --> 01:42:38,980
they don't have a lot of money, whatever,

1579
01:42:38,980 --> 01:42:40,380
but they're superstars.

1580
01:42:40,380 --> 01:42:44,100
Not only do they believe in that, they also believe in,

1581
01:42:44,100 --> 01:42:48,940
it's OK if you try very hard and then fail at the end.

1582
01:42:48,940 --> 01:42:50,820
That's OK also.

1583
01:42:50,820 --> 01:42:55,220
So a ton of people are going to really hard math and science

1584
01:42:55,220 --> 01:42:59,020
training and coming out, failing because the competition is

1585
01:42:59,020 --> 01:43:01,420
just so intense.

1586
01:43:01,420 --> 01:43:09,420
But people still do it anyway, and they devote a lot of years

1587
01:43:09,420 --> 01:43:12,420
and lives into it.

1588
01:43:12,420 --> 01:43:20,740
I think that probably the best way

1589
01:43:20,740 --> 01:43:27,860
that people love hard problems is to, from childhood,

1590
01:43:27,860 --> 01:43:33,900
raise them in communities where all their peers are all

1591
01:43:33,900 --> 01:43:38,140
into science, because that's what they're into.

1592
01:43:38,140 --> 01:43:42,700
I had this experience of switching between on Long

1593
01:43:42,700 --> 01:43:44,700
Island, switching between high schools,

1594
01:43:44,700 --> 01:43:46,540
switching between junior high.

1595
01:43:46,540 --> 01:43:49,940
I was at a junior high for literally three miles away

1596
01:43:50,140 --> 01:43:52,140
from the junior high where I ended up finishing.

1597
01:43:52,140 --> 01:43:56,140
And the whole atmosphere of the first junior high

1598
01:43:56,140 --> 01:43:57,140
was just awful.

1599
01:43:57,140 --> 01:44:03,140
It was just these, no one cooled into science.

1600
01:44:03,140 --> 01:44:10,140
And so it was very, when you create people where the norm

1601
01:44:10,140 --> 01:44:13,140
is people who are math, science nerds,

1602
01:44:13,140 --> 01:44:19,140
if you create more of those places where they self-label

1603
01:44:19,340 --> 01:44:23,340
that way, people who are kind of on the edge,

1604
01:44:23,340 --> 01:44:26,340
people like, should I do math and science?

1605
01:44:26,340 --> 01:44:30,340
Or should I just make music or something

1606
01:44:30,340 --> 01:44:32,340
for the rest of my life?

1607
01:44:32,340 --> 01:44:36,340
They'll be more likely to just get swept up in that.

1608
01:44:36,340 --> 01:44:39,340
I think you need a place to be socialized

1609
01:44:39,340 --> 01:44:41,340
to be interested in math.

1610
01:44:41,540 --> 01:44:50,540
Let's ask a question of how much does what you're learning

1611
01:44:50,540 --> 01:44:53,540
interact with real life?

1612
01:44:53,540 --> 01:44:58,540
I went to a high school of science, which was great.

1613
01:44:58,540 --> 01:45:05,540
I remember in grade school, science was really nice.

1614
01:45:05,540 --> 01:45:08,540
And of course, it was pretty hard sometimes.

1615
01:45:09,340 --> 01:45:11,900
But then there are other things like history,

1616
01:45:11,900 --> 01:45:13,420
and that was incredibly hard.

1617
01:45:17,220 --> 01:45:19,500
How come some kids don't find history

1618
01:45:19,500 --> 01:45:22,380
is completely incomprehensible?

1619
01:45:22,380 --> 01:45:26,300
Makes no sense, and you can't figure out

1620
01:45:26,300 --> 01:45:30,360
what will happen next except by looking it up.

1621
01:45:30,360 --> 01:45:31,820
And how come most of the children

1622
01:45:31,820 --> 01:45:36,460
don't realize that this is too hard to pay any attention to?

1623
01:45:36,860 --> 01:45:40,860
I think they do realize it, but they don't pay attention to it.

1624
01:45:40,860 --> 01:45:42,460
Do most people hate history?

1625
01:45:42,460 --> 01:45:43,340
I think so.

1626
01:45:43,340 --> 01:45:43,840
Oh, good.

1627
01:45:43,840 --> 01:45:44,820
What was that, really?

1628
01:45:44,820 --> 01:45:47,260
I'm sorry.

1629
01:45:47,260 --> 01:45:49,980
I thought people took it for granted.

1630
01:45:49,980 --> 01:45:53,420
And I don't know, when I took history,

1631
01:45:53,420 --> 01:45:55,780
I think what I got out most from that class

1632
01:45:55,780 --> 01:45:59,860
wasn't the history itself, but rather how to frame ideas

1633
01:45:59,860 --> 01:46:02,660
and how to make a good argument and support it

1634
01:46:02,660 --> 01:46:04,500
and how to write a good paper, which are

1635
01:46:04,500 --> 01:46:06,460
kind of essential life skills.

1636
01:46:06,460 --> 01:46:08,460
Right, but even the best argument

1637
01:46:08,460 --> 01:46:15,540
isn't very good in that field, so it's very tough.

1638
01:46:15,540 --> 01:46:19,180
Well, I guess if it's hard to find exceptions,

1639
01:46:19,180 --> 01:46:25,580
then that gets interesting, even if the thing is wrong.

1640
01:46:25,580 --> 01:46:28,460
I'm not sure what I'm saying.

1641
01:46:28,460 --> 01:46:34,860
But if a subject has the word science in it,

1642
01:46:34,860 --> 01:46:39,780
it isn't social science and things.

1643
01:46:39,780 --> 01:46:42,540
I think with the issue of science,

1644
01:46:42,540 --> 01:46:45,660
there's no one solution of how to get people

1645
01:46:45,660 --> 01:46:47,300
motivated in science, right?

1646
01:46:47,300 --> 01:46:49,380
But there are several different factors.

1647
01:46:49,380 --> 01:46:52,220
So one factor is definitely the idea

1648
01:46:52,220 --> 01:46:55,260
of having a social support network,

1649
01:46:55,260 --> 01:46:58,060
whether it's teachers who support you

1650
01:46:58,060 --> 01:47:01,260
and also having peers who don't make fun of you

1651
01:47:01,260 --> 01:47:03,820
and ostracize you for liking science and that.

1652
01:47:03,820 --> 01:47:04,700
That's one.

1653
01:47:04,700 --> 01:47:08,300
Two, I think the curriculum itself also

1654
01:47:08,300 --> 01:47:09,460
has something to do with it.

1655
01:47:09,460 --> 01:47:11,300
As you said, I think it helps more

1656
01:47:11,300 --> 01:47:14,900
when people can connect it better to the real world,

1657
01:47:14,900 --> 01:47:15,900
to life.

1658
01:47:15,900 --> 01:47:20,780
And I think it also helps more when people are sort of allowed

1659
01:47:20,780 --> 01:47:23,420
a bit of creativity, if you will,

1660
01:47:23,420 --> 01:47:27,700
when they're not stuck doing growth problems all the time.

1661
01:47:27,700 --> 01:47:30,380
And I think another issue is sort

1662
01:47:30,380 --> 01:47:34,540
of presenting problems and solutions and lessons

1663
01:47:34,540 --> 01:47:37,660
to students in such a way that they're sufficiently

1664
01:47:37,660 --> 01:47:40,500
challenged, but they're not discouraged

1665
01:47:40,500 --> 01:47:42,620
because it's too difficult. And on the other hand,

1666
01:47:42,620 --> 01:47:46,540
they're not bored because it's too repetitive.

1667
01:47:46,540 --> 01:47:49,580
So I think it's sort of like a delicate balance, right?

1668
01:47:49,580 --> 01:47:52,740
All these factors must be there.

1669
01:47:52,740 --> 01:47:57,300
Yeah, and that also relates to the hour problem,

1670
01:47:57,300 --> 01:48:02,940
like when can you give someone a problem that

1671
01:48:02,940 --> 01:48:07,140
might take a whole day or two?

1672
01:48:07,140 --> 01:48:13,500
And there's no place for that in, well, there must be.

1673
01:48:13,500 --> 01:48:15,980
Where in school do you get, that's

1674
01:48:15,980 --> 01:48:19,820
when you have to write a term paper, maybe.

1675
01:48:19,820 --> 01:48:22,780
And I think another thing about science and math,

1676
01:48:22,780 --> 01:48:26,900
perhaps, at least the grade school incarnations

1677
01:48:26,900 --> 01:48:29,340
of those subjects, is that they tend

1678
01:48:29,340 --> 01:48:34,340
to be a lot more isolating than subjects in the humanities,

1679
01:48:34,340 --> 01:48:37,620
in the sense that when you're stuck at home doing science

1680
01:48:37,620 --> 01:48:39,620
and math problems, you're always by yourself.

1681
01:48:39,620 --> 01:48:44,940
And you're always encouraged to essentially quarantine

1682
01:48:44,940 --> 01:48:48,460
yourself to study these things and come up with solutions.

1683
01:48:48,460 --> 01:48:52,860
Whereas classes in history or foreign languages or English

1684
01:48:52,860 --> 01:48:55,260
are more like discussion space.

1685
01:48:55,260 --> 01:48:57,620
And actually, I think that's sort of, I don't know,

1686
01:48:57,620 --> 01:49:00,020
because in real life, when you solve scientific problems,

1687
01:49:00,020 --> 01:49:02,100
you are working on a team a lot of the time.

1688
01:49:02,100 --> 01:49:04,380
And you have to communicate your ideas.

1689
01:49:04,380 --> 01:49:06,540
And you kind of are working together.

1690
01:49:06,540 --> 01:49:08,940
But somehow, in grade school, you're

1691
01:49:08,940 --> 01:49:12,780
stuck working on these problems by yourself.

1692
01:49:12,780 --> 01:49:15,500
I think that might also be a contributing factor.

1693
01:49:15,500 --> 01:49:17,540
Interesting.

1694
01:49:17,540 --> 01:49:22,500
Well, if you try to solve a geometry problem,

1695
01:49:22,500 --> 01:49:26,820
have you ever solved a problem working with someone else?

1696
01:49:26,820 --> 01:49:27,420
Does it help?

1697
01:49:27,420 --> 01:49:31,580
Or are they always interrupting you so you can't concentrate?

1698
01:49:31,580 --> 01:49:35,780
In undergrad, for instance, there will be office hours

1699
01:49:35,780 --> 01:49:39,060
or open office hours where students all come together

1700
01:49:39,060 --> 01:49:43,220
and help each other a little or give hints, things like that.

1701
01:49:43,220 --> 01:49:47,060
And it tends to help for at least most people.

1702
01:49:47,060 --> 01:49:50,740
But I guess I'm mostly encountering the other people

1703
01:49:50,740 --> 01:49:54,220
who go to these things.

1704
01:49:54,220 --> 01:49:56,380
I think in grade school, it's too,

1705
01:49:56,380 --> 01:50:00,060
one, the problems that you have to master are too simple.

1706
01:50:02,940 --> 01:50:07,220
It only requires one flash of insight to solve the problem.

1707
01:50:07,220 --> 01:50:09,060
And that flash of insight you're supposed

1708
01:50:09,060 --> 01:50:10,860
to work towards on your own.

1709
01:50:10,860 --> 01:50:15,620
Whereas if there's a problem that takes a day to solve,

1710
01:50:15,620 --> 01:50:18,940
that takes five flashes of insight,

1711
01:50:18,940 --> 01:50:22,580
consecutive flashes of insight to solve it,

1712
01:50:22,580 --> 01:50:24,380
then it's a collaborative.

1713
01:50:24,380 --> 01:50:25,540
OK, here's a problem.

1714
01:50:35,540 --> 01:50:36,700
There's an isosceles.

1715
01:50:36,700 --> 01:50:38,700
These two sides are equal.

1716
01:50:38,700 --> 01:50:40,340
So that's an isosceles triangle.

1717
01:50:41,340 --> 01:50:49,580
So now, here are two angle bisectors.

1718
01:50:56,500 --> 01:50:59,580
So if the triangle is isosceles, prove

1719
01:50:59,580 --> 01:51:01,660
that the angle bisectors are equal.

1720
01:51:05,220 --> 01:51:06,860
Has anybody proved it yet?

1721
01:51:11,340 --> 01:51:13,140
Well, it's very easy.

1722
01:51:15,580 --> 01:51:18,540
But here's your homework.

1723
01:51:18,540 --> 01:51:22,820
If you have a triangle and the angle bisectors are equal,

1724
01:51:22,820 --> 01:51:27,460
prove that the corresponding sides are equal.

1725
01:51:27,460 --> 01:51:31,580
And see who can get the shortest proof.

1726
01:51:31,580 --> 01:51:33,100
It's pretty hard.

1727
01:51:33,100 --> 01:51:35,780
Have you ever read the essay by Paul Lockhart

1728
01:51:35,780 --> 01:51:39,180
called A Mathematician's Limit?

1729
01:51:39,180 --> 01:51:40,540
What's the third word?

1730
01:51:40,540 --> 01:51:42,860
A mathematician's lament.

1731
01:51:42,860 --> 01:51:43,620
Living?

1732
01:51:43,620 --> 01:51:44,580
Lament.

1733
01:51:44,580 --> 01:51:45,900
Lament.

1734
01:51:45,900 --> 01:51:47,700
No, I don't think so.

1735
01:51:47,700 --> 01:51:50,980
It's sort of his critique on math education in America.

1736
01:51:50,980 --> 01:51:53,820
It's quite interesting.

1737
01:51:53,820 --> 01:51:56,020
Yeah, I was just thinking that, well,

1738
01:51:56,020 --> 01:51:59,780
you mentioned that mathematics tends to be pretty slow.

1739
01:51:59,780 --> 01:52:02,820
But Marvin brought up that, and I

1740
01:52:02,820 --> 01:52:07,740
was thinking that for many kinds of mathematical problems,

1741
01:52:07,740 --> 01:52:13,700
you can prove theorems in different ways.

1742
01:52:13,700 --> 01:52:17,020
And then somebody comes up with a proof,

1743
01:52:17,020 --> 01:52:21,180
and then you challenge that, OK, now somebody else

1744
01:52:21,180 --> 01:52:22,940
finds another kind of proof.

1745
01:52:22,940 --> 01:52:23,740
Better, please.

1746
01:52:23,740 --> 01:52:26,020
You can have a homework of, OK, come up

1747
01:52:26,020 --> 01:52:28,820
with four different ways of proving this thing.

1748
01:52:28,820 --> 01:52:32,780
And always, everything goes.

1749
01:52:32,780 --> 01:52:35,060
So if you want to work together with people,

1750
01:52:35,060 --> 01:52:37,700
you can pull out your proofs.

1751
01:52:37,700 --> 01:52:44,380
So that's why Feynman said he was so great.

1752
01:52:44,380 --> 01:52:47,060
That is, when he had a physics problem,

1753
01:52:47,060 --> 01:52:51,020
he forced himself to find several different ways.

1754
01:52:51,020 --> 01:52:52,580
And he said all of his friends, when

1755
01:52:52,580 --> 01:52:57,100
they learned quantum mechanics, either learned the Heisenberg

1756
01:52:57,100 --> 01:53:05,260
matrix method or the Schrodinger differential equation method

1757
01:53:05,260 --> 01:53:08,700
or the Dirac technique.

1758
01:53:08,700 --> 01:53:12,740
And whenever he had a problem, he

1759
01:53:12,740 --> 01:53:16,780
would solve it by all known techniques.

1760
01:53:16,780 --> 01:53:20,100
And then in later life, he rarely

1761
01:53:20,100 --> 01:53:23,420
got stuck where most people did.

1762
01:53:23,420 --> 01:53:24,100
Yeah?

1763
01:53:24,100 --> 01:53:30,420
So related to that, the best mathematicians that I know

1764
01:53:30,420 --> 01:53:33,420
are people that they stay with a problem,

1765
01:53:33,420 --> 01:53:36,900
and they solve by themselves.

1766
01:53:36,900 --> 01:53:39,860
They don't go and look for the solution

1767
01:53:39,860 --> 01:53:41,940
or ask other people.

1768
01:53:41,940 --> 01:53:43,460
They try to solve it by themselves.

1769
01:53:43,460 --> 01:53:45,300
And I believe it's just because of the way

1770
01:53:45,300 --> 01:53:48,180
we created pathways.

1771
01:53:48,180 --> 01:53:50,620
I believe that's a-

1772
01:53:50,620 --> 01:53:54,420
But there are quite a few pairs of mathematicians.

1773
01:53:54,420 --> 01:53:58,260
Yeah, but when you're young, you should

1774
01:53:58,260 --> 01:54:00,300
try to solve the problems by yourself,

1775
01:54:00,300 --> 01:54:02,820
at least when you're in middle school or high school.

1776
01:54:02,820 --> 01:54:04,740
And then you create these pathways.

1777
01:54:04,740 --> 01:54:06,100
Right.

1778
01:54:06,100 --> 01:54:10,020
Maybe when you get older, the problems are too hard.

1779
01:54:10,020 --> 01:54:15,740
And then it doesn't help to solve the problem by yourself,

1780
01:54:15,740 --> 01:54:18,460
because you're not going to solve harder problems

1781
01:54:18,460 --> 01:54:19,860
than those ones.

1782
01:54:24,660 --> 01:54:26,300
How many of you have ever solved a math

1783
01:54:26,300 --> 01:54:29,380
problem with someone else?

1784
01:54:29,380 --> 01:54:31,660
Quite a few.

1785
01:54:31,660 --> 01:54:33,260
It seemed like they could solve it.

1786
01:54:37,260 --> 01:54:40,340
I remember being in a boat with Seymour Papert,

1787
01:54:40,340 --> 01:54:42,260
solving some really hard problem.

1788
01:54:45,780 --> 01:54:50,500
And after a while, he got tired of it

1789
01:54:50,500 --> 01:54:55,660
and slipped into the water and went swimming around.

1790
01:54:55,660 --> 01:55:00,300
And I said, come back.

1791
01:55:00,300 --> 01:55:01,100
He said, why?

1792
01:55:01,100 --> 01:55:04,100
And I said, I'll tell you when you get here.

1793
01:55:04,100 --> 01:55:07,020
And he got back before the shark.

1794
01:55:07,020 --> 01:55:10,980
Did I ever tell you about it?

1795
01:55:10,980 --> 01:55:15,300
We thought it was a dolphin for a while.

1796
01:55:15,300 --> 01:55:18,540
But it had this fin on the back that didn't seem quite right.

1797
01:55:18,540 --> 01:55:19,040
OK.

1798
01:55:24,620 --> 01:55:28,500
Anyway, I did a lot of solving with.

1799
01:55:31,220 --> 01:55:34,660
I don't remember ever solving a hard problem with three people.

